Anonymous - I'm sorry for the delay in a response to you, but your post really touched me and I wanted something of substance to offer you. I have enlisted e-mail friends of mine and I have some sites to offer to for assist.<br><br>
But first, let me say that, from the sound of it, you did the best you could trying to take care of him, yourself and your daughter. YOU COULD NOT DO MORE FOR HIM THAN HE ALLOWED YOU TO DO! I take this quote from a dear friend of mine, but I know this to be true. I have been married to the same woman for twenty five years. In many of those years, I put her through a living hell. Much was unnecessary, had I taken the responsibility to ask for help from her and others. You did listen, I'm sure, when he did talk. You did the best you could for him, for yourself, and your daughter! He owns responsibility in his actions, you should not burden yourself with both yours and his. I don't know you or your situation. I would never presume to know what you are going through. But, I have a feeling that you were not pushing him away. You were using what tools that you had on hand at the time to make things work for everyone.<br><br>
Ok, I'll get off the soapbox. Here are some things that may be of assistance to you. There is a woman by the name of Patience Mason who puts out a PTSD newsletter, &quot;The Post-Traumatic Gazette&quot;. She has also written books, the best, or best known is &quot;A Woman's Guide to Helping Your Vietnam Veteran, Your Family, and Yourself&quot;. This, in itself may help you understand him better for your own peace of mind. But the immediate things available is that she (Patience) has a semi-interactive web page (PTSD 101) where you can discuss you, your situation, and your feelings. She personally answers you. On these sites, her e-mail address is also available, if you wanted to back-channel with her.<br>
Here are the addresses:<br><br>
Her home page (The Post-Traumatic Gazette) is <br>
http://www.mindspring.com/~ptg/ptg.html<br><br>
Her interactive site (PTSD 101)is http://grunt.space.swri.edu/patience/<br><br>
There is one other address that may have something for you. It is the Vietnam Veterans Home Page. The address is:<br><br>
http://www.viet.org/index.htm<br><br>
If nothing else, these places are a starting point. Patience probably can lead you to other resources better than I, but, if not, e-mail me or post here.<br><br>
My best to you!<br><br>
Debbie - If you are reading this, these are also for you! Check these sites out and see if they help you in your situation.
